00:50:57,148 --> 00:50:58,148
[Munching]

806
00:50:58,339 --> 00:51:01,801
Good money?
- No, not really.

807
00:51:02,152 --> 00:51:03,152
So then?

808
00:51:03,816 --> 00:51:08,238
I mean not at the level at
which I am currently working.

809
00:51:08,239 --> 00:51:10,758
And I haven't yet
explored all my options.

810
00:51:11,419 --> 00:51:12,419
Why not?

811
00:51:14,732 --> 00:51:15,732
I'm not sure.

812
00:51:16,560 --> 00:51:19,560
If you interrogate her, how
do you expect her to open up?

813
00:51:21,093 --> 00:51:22,527
There should be
some comfort level first.

814
00:51:22,528 --> 00:51:24,968
Let her get comfortable, she'll
answer you in five languages.

815
00:51:25,188 --> 00:51:26,469
[Phone vibrates]

816
00:51:27,126 --> 00:51:28,407
[Phone vibrates]

817
00:51:30,247 --> 00:51:30,920
Excuse me.

818
00:51:30,921 --> 00:51:32,185
[Shifts chair]

819
00:51:33,378 --> 00:51:35,469
[Water splashing]

820
00:51:35,677 --> 00:51:38,360
[Water splashing]

821
00:51:38,842 --> 00:51:40,812
[Exhales]

822
00:51:43,144 --> 00:51:47,743
Is he coming back?
- Not if you're going to start crying again.

823
00:51:48,764 --> 00:51:51,060
We're never coming here again.
- Okay, let's not.

824
00:51:51,264 --> 00:51:53,184
I feel physical pain from
being around that man.

825
00:51:53,589 --> 00:51:55,308
I don't know how Mom tolerates him.

826
00:51:55,309 --> 00:51:58,363
I've told her so many times to leave
him; that I'll support her if she does.

827
00:52:00,122 --> 00:52:03,619
I don't want that man in my life.
- Why did you have to speak for me?

828
00:52:04,309 --> 00:52:06,537
I was trying to defend you!
- I was doing just fine.

829
00:52:06,538 --> 00:52:07,276
But it was for you!

830
00:52:07,506 --> 00:52:09,039
[Sighs]

831
00:52:09,229 --> 00:52:10,229
See!

832
00:52:10,878 --> 00:52:12,509
We're fighting because of him!

833
00:52:15,674 --> 00:52:17,601
[Car beeps]

834
00:52:18,783 --> 00:52:20,951
[Car door shuts]

835
00:52:21,181 --> 00:52:22,320
[Muffled cry]

836
00:52:26,064 --> 00:52:27,064
[Sniffs]

837
00:52:28,320 --> 00:52:30,575
[Sniffs]

838
00:52:32,776 --> 00:52:33,958
[Sniffs]

839
00:52:36,586 --> 00:52:37,714
You're too good for me.

840
00:52:40,302 --> 00:52:41,305
He could see it.

841
00:52:43,966 --> 00:52:48,947
I think everyone can.
- Okay, enough. Let's go home.

842
00:52:49,473 --> 00:52:51,367
[Staring]

843
00:52:52,834 --> 00:52:54,893
[Encouraging look]

844
00:52:55,347 --> 00:52:57,082
Let's never look at his face again.

845
00:52:59,425 --> 00:53:00,425
Okay. Never again.

846
00:53:00,805 --> 00:53:01,845
Hi!

847
00:53:02,502 --> 00:53:04,812
[Clangs]

848
00:53:05,196 --> 00:53:06,214
[Birds chirping]

849
00:53:06,717 --> 00:53:10,867
Did you change the display again?

850
00:53:11,080 --> 00:53:14,179
Yes, you asked me to.

851
00:53:14,180 --> 00:53:18,025
No, I said keep all the Tsukudani

852
00:53:18,026 --> 00:53:20,976
at the bottom and the
boiled beans on top.

853
00:53:20,977 --> 00:53:23,380
That was yesterday.

854
00:53:23,675 --> 00:53:25,865
Not yesterday. I
told you this morning.

855
00:53:26,216 --> 00:53:27,880
[Clangs]

856
00:53:29,579 --> 00:53:34,610
What you just had
was Shiro Miso. Okay?

857
00:53:35,333 --> 00:53:36,333
[Chuckles]

858
00:53:36,663 --> 00:53:37,928
The one before?

859
00:53:39,165 --> 00:53:40,165
Uh.

860
00:53:40,582 --> 00:53:45,685
Komi? Kome Miso?
- Yes! He's a professional.

861
00:53:45,686 --> 00:53:47,366
[Chuckles]

862
00:53:47,760 --> 00:53:48,800
[Chuckles]

863
00:53:50,924 --> 00:53:53,420
You should try some eel.

864
00:53:53,421 --> 00:53:57,724
Try the Yamato simmered
eel with Tsukudani.

865
00:53:58,501 --> 00:54:00,264
When do you leave?

866
00:54:01,872 --> 00:54:02,875
In another two days.

867
00:54:03,685 --> 00:54:07,035
Come back towards the end of
March to see the cherry blossoms.

868
00:54:07,172 --> 00:54:09,269
And we have to go to Fuji.
- Of course.

869
00:54:17,918 --> 00:54:18,918
I'm home.

870
00:54:19,378 --> 00:54:25,026
Fuji-san is everywhere. On walls,
on T-shirts, on thousand yen bills.

871
00:54:26,112 --> 00:54:29,536
You can see Fuji from anywhere.

872
00:54:30,185 --> 00:54:34,293
Tokyo Tower,
Shinkansen, even the plane!

873
00:54:34,739 --> 00:54:41,028
But if you're not lucky,
you won't see it at all.

874
00:54:41,755 --> 00:54:43,744
It's a moody mountain.

875
00:54:44,322 --> 00:54:49,054
Just like that, it will
decide not to open

876
00:54:49,954 --> 00:54:51,338
its heart to you.

877
00:54:51,767 --> 00:54:54,350
And if you're very very very lucky,

878
00:54:54,351 --> 00:54:56,365
on a clear day,
you can see it upside down,

879
00:54:56,366 --> 00:54:58,774
reflected perfectly
in the lake below.

880
00:54:59,922 --> 00:55:02,162
I am sorry, but I really don't
understand what can happen

881
00:55:02,931 --> 00:55:04,517
by just looking at it?

882
00:55:05,369 --> 00:55:07,039
A lot can happen.

883
00:55:08,023 --> 00:55:13,030
As you share a
silence with Fuji-san,

884
00:55:13,705 --> 00:55:14,852
[Grins]

885
00:55:15,172 --> 00:55:20,817
You may be able to hear yourself.

886
00:55:21,045 --> 00:55:22,312
[Tense silence]

887
00:55:22,313 --> 00:55:29,655
The mountain can help you see
something you've been blind to.

888
00:55:30,233 --> 00:55:32,800
[Tense music]

889
00:55:38,055 --> 00:55:40,394
[Tense music]

890
00:55:41,518 --> 00:55:43,673
Ma?
- Hmm?

891
00:55:45,347 --> 00:55:46,347
May I say something?

892
00:55:48,622 --> 00:55:49,671
Hmm.

893
00:55:49,672 --> 00:55:50,672
He is a good guy.

894
00:55:51,672 --> 00:55:53,781
What was he like
when you were friends?

895
00:55:56,894 --> 00:55:59,110
[Sighs]

896
00:56:00,438 --> 00:56:01,438
He was?

897
00:56:03,008 --> 00:56:04,760
The sweetest boy that I met.

898
00:56:06,503 --> 00:56:08,754
Why didn't you stay in touch?

899
00:56:10,059 --> 00:56:11,338
[Sighs]

900
00:56:11,557 --> 00:56:14,044
Because we had a fight.
- Over what?

901
00:56:15,726 --> 00:56:16,856
Hmm.

902
00:56:18,105 --> 00:56:19,471
It was a grown up fight, Kartu.

903
00:56:19,944 --> 00:56:20,721
[Sighs]

904
00:56:20,722 --> 00:56:22,966
You won't understand yet.
- Okay.

905
00:56:23,781 --> 00:56:25,515
[Sighs]

906
00:56:26,222 --> 00:56:28,116
Are you cold?
- Yes.

907
00:56:28,659 --> 00:56:29,659
Come.

908
00:56:29,746 --> 00:56:31,322
[Footsteps]

909
00:56:32,382 --> 00:56:34,178
[Muffled rustling]

910
00:56:36,841 --> 00:56:37,841
[Sighs]

911
00:56:40,239 --> 00:56:41,579
[Clangs]

912
00:56:43,047 --> 00:56:44,995
Ma?
- Hmm?

913
00:56:45,255 --> 00:56:48,052
May I say something?
- Hmm?

914
00:56:48,595 --> 00:56:49,892
[Gulps]

915
00:56:50,180 --> 00:56:51,915
I think he likes me.

916
00:56:52,607 --> 00:56:54,026
[Stares]

917
00:56:54,262 --> 00:56:57,433
Obviously. Everybody likes you.

918
00:56:57,731 --> 00:56:58,388
[Sighs]

919
00:56:58,580 --> 00:57:00,113
That's what you think.

920
00:57:00,280 --> 00:57:04,125
But some of my classmates
don't like me. Okay?

921
00:57:04,765 --> 00:57:05,765
Okay.

922
00:57:06,789 --> 00:57:10,283
Let's tell him to
come to Tokyo again.

923
00:57:12,214 --> 00:57:13,401
Okay. Let's.

924
00:57:13,988 --> 00:57:14,988
For sure?

925
00:57:19,918 --> 00:57:20,918
Hmm.

926
00:57:25,630 --> 00:57:27,495
Not sleepy?
- No.

927
00:57:28,151 --> 00:57:29,667
[Clock ticks]

928
00:57:30,289 --> 00:57:33,573
Shall we read something?
- No. You are tired.

929
00:57:35,019 --> 00:57:36,438
Umm.

930
00:57:37,722 --> 00:57:38,722
Let us.

931
00:57:41,781 --> 00:57:43,892
[Paper ruffles]

932
00:57:46,335 --> 00:57:48,035
[Sighs]

933
00:57:50,540 --> 00:57:52,204
[Exhales]

934
00:57:59,089 --> 00:58:00,823
[Rustles]

935
00:58:01,217 --> 00:58:02,417
[Rustles]

936
00:58:03,705 --> 00:58:05,033
[Rustles]

937
00:58:05,034 --> 00:58:06,061
So?

938
00:58:07,555 --> 00:58:12,569
For four thousand years, the
volcano had remained quiet.

939
00:58:13,319 --> 00:58:13,906
Hmm.

940
00:58:14,291 --> 00:58:15,439
But recently,

941
00:58:16,603 --> 00:58:19,336
something inside it began to stir.

942
00:58:20,720 --> 00:58:22,542
[Knock]

943
00:58:23,199 --> 00:58:24,199
[Door opens]

944
00:58:24,548 --> 00:58:25,548
[Clangs]

945
00:58:27,430 --> 00:58:29,462
[Clangs]

946
00:58:31,555 --> 00:58:34,204
[Laughs]

947
00:58:35,860 --> 00:58:37,074
[Dancing]

948
00:58:37,075 --> 00:58:38,190
Spic and span.

949
00:58:38,724 --> 00:58:39,828
[Whistles]

950
00:58:40,005 --> 00:58:42,526
Clean, clean, clean.

951
00:58:43,005 --> 00:58:44,785
Sparkling clean.

952
00:58:45,994 --> 00:58:46,994
[Thuds]

953
00:58:47,672 --> 00:58:48,672
Nice.

954
00:58:49,589 --> 00:58:51,638
Not bad.
- I know, I know, I know.

955
00:58:51,639 --> 00:58:52,639
Not bad.

956
00:58:53,297 --> 00:58:54,297
You are drenched.

957
00:58:54,755 --> 00:58:56,675
My bike broke down
and it was pouring.

958
00:58:57,797 --> 00:58:59,860
Weren't you supposed to go to the office only once a week?
- Yes.

959
00:58:59,861 --> 00:59:00,861
[Sighs]

960
00:59:01,326 --> 00:59:02,326
So then, how come today?

961
00:59:03,017 --> 00:59:04,505
It's a complicated copy.

962
00:59:04,506 --> 00:59:07,638
It's some report for the comparative
study of three pesticides.

963
00:59:07,639 --> 00:59:08,639
What's for dinner?

964
00:59:09,559 --> 00:59:10,559
Pasta!

965
00:59:11,091 --> 00:59:12,361
[Moves hand]

966
00:59:13,264 --> 00:59:14,264
Nice.

967
00:59:14,499 --> 00:59:15,686
[Jumping]

968
00:59:15,687 --> 00:59:16,687
[Thuds]

969
00:59:23,039 --> 00:59:24,642
[Clicks]

970
00:59:26,113 --> 00:59:27,113
[Thuds]

971
00:59:29,354 --> 00:59:30,354
[Clangs]

972
00:59:30,651 --> 00:59:32,087
[Clicks]

973
00:59:32,621 --> 00:59:34,075
[Unwrapping]

974
00:59:34,575 --> 00:59:36,107
[Unwrapping]

975
00:59:36,432 --> 00:59:38,008
[Rattling]

976
00:59:39,506 --> 00:59:40,506
[Clangs]

977
00:59:41,810 --> 00:59:43,535
[Sizzling]

978
00:59:43,667 --> 00:59:45,795
[Stirring]

979
00:59:46,750 --> 00:59:48,721
[Sizzling]

980
00:59:48,931 --> 00:59:51,077
[Sizzling]

981
00:59:53,258 --> 00:59:54,388
[Knocking]

982
00:59:55,132 --> 00:59:56,132
[Clangs]

983
00:59:57,418 --> 00:59:58,418
[Opens the cover]

984
00:59:59,089 --> 01:00:00,432
Shall I help?
- No.

985
01:00:00,907 --> 01:00:01,907
What should I chop?

986
01:00:02,253 --> 01:00:04,960
[Singing]

987
01:00:05,775 --> 01:00:08,814
[Singing]

988
01:00:09,191 --> 01:00:12,423
[Singing/Groaning]

989
01:00:13,229 --> 01:00:15,305
[Singing]

990
01:00:15,778 --> 01:00:16,496
[Singing]

991
01:00:16,618 --> 01:00:18,614
Why do you have so much
energy at this time of the day?

992
01:00:18,615 --> 01:00:23,065
'I have the power!'

993
01:00:23,783 --> 01:00:25,885
[Sizzling]

994
01:00:26,586 --> 01:00:28,127
[Thunder rumbling]

995
01:00:28,995 --> 01:00:30,282
[Sizzling]

996
01:00:31,657 --> 01:00:32,779
[Thunder rumbling]

997
01:00:37,894 --> 01:00:38,894
[Spread]

998
01:00:40,416 --> 01:00:41,416
[Clangs]

999
01:00:45,155 --> 01:00:46,259
[Thunder rumbling]

1000
01:00:52,504 --> 01:00:53,504
[Grunts]

1001
01:01:00,124 --> 01:01:01,517
[Thunder rattling]

1002
01:01:01,692 --> 01:01:02,717
[Sighs]

1003
01:01:02,857 --> 01:01:03,857
I need money.

1004
01:01:05,593 --> 01:01:06,593
A lot of it.

1005
01:01:08,608 --> 01:01:09,608
A lot of it.

1006
01:01:10,141 --> 01:01:11,437
[Sighs]

1007
01:01:13,390 --> 01:01:15,016
[Breathing heavily]

1008
01:01:15,017 --> 01:01:18,085
I have to return all the money I
borrowed through my mum's treatment.

1009
01:01:19,555 --> 01:01:23,130
I have to return money to
relatives. I have to repay the loan.

1010
01:01:23,297 --> 01:01:26,135
Okay.
- It's a lot.

1011
01:01:26,555 --> 01:01:29,892
Okay, okay. Calm down.

1012
01:01:30,944 --> 01:01:31,944
[Sniffs]

1013
01:01:32,972 --> 01:01:36,295
I can understand the stress. But?

1014
01:01:36,630 --> 01:01:39,431
There's no need to panic.
We'll manage somehow.

1015
01:01:39,714 --> 01:01:44,021
This is the last thought on my mind when I
go to sleep and the first when I wake up.

1016
01:01:44,240 --> 01:01:45,638
[Sobbing]

1017
01:01:45,639 --> 01:01:49,627
We'll figure it out.
- How?

1018
01:01:50,231 --> 01:01:52,228
[Sizzling]

1019
01:01:53,672 --> 01:01:57,449
There's always a way. Money
isn't worth thinking about so much.

1020
01:01:58,053 --> 01:01:59,840
[Sizzling]

1021
01:02:00,716 --> 01:02:02,643
[Sizzling]

1022
01:02:05,231 --> 01:02:06,957
[Munching]

1023
01:02:08,087 --> 01:02:09,322
[Munching]

1024
01:02:10,014 --> 01:02:11,328
Let's ask dad?

1025
01:02:13,639 --> 01:02:14,061
Whom?

1026
01:02:14,222 --> 01:02:15,952
It's a negligible
amount for your dad.

1027
01:02:15,953 --> 01:02:17,985
And we'll return
every penny. We will?

1028
01:02:19,247 --> 01:02:20,247
What?

1029
01:02:21,199 --> 01:02:24,063
You know how much
I despise that man.

1030
01:02:24,464 --> 01:02:28,653
You have a right to that money. Why
should we have to beg for it elsewhere?

1031
01:02:29,626 --> 01:02:32,463
Why can't we find a way on our own?

1032
01:02:34,250 --> 01:02:38,087
How are we going to do that?
Please tell me. I'm all ears.

1033
01:02:39,714 --> 01:02:43,141
What do we do?
- How can I come up with an instant solution just like that?

1034
01:02:45,464 --> 01:02:47,135
But there is always a way.

1035
01:02:48,005 --> 01:02:49,798
Like there was with your funding?

1036
01:03:06,214 --> 01:03:08,536
I pay the rent. I
pay all the bills.

1037
01:03:08,823 --> 01:03:12,410
I pay the maid. I cover most
of the household expenses.

1038
01:03:12,411 --> 01:03:14,472
I am translating anything
that comes my way.

1039
01:03:15,891 --> 01:03:17,827
I have no relief.

1040
01:03:18,547 --> 01:03:26,324
I'm sick of negotiating, of begging people to pay me 40
paise per word instead of 25; if not 40, 35 at least.

1041
01:03:26,325 --> 01:03:27,437
[Tense music]

1042
01:03:27,962 --> 01:03:30,476
[Water splashing]

1043
01:03:30,809 --> 01:03:31,939
[Sighs]

1044
01:03:34,383 --> 01:03:35,383
[Tense music]

1045
01:03:36,514 --> 01:03:37,852
How do you manage your expenses?

1046
01:03:38,847 --> 01:03:40,418
The eating and
drinking out? Petrol?

1047
01:03:41,589 --> 01:03:44,421
Mom sends some money each month.

1048
01:03:45,402 --> 01:03:46,402
Very little.

1049
01:03:47,552 --> 01:03:50,765
You won't even have to meet him.

1050
01:03:50,766 --> 01:03:54,097
Please, please, please? please!

1051
01:03:55,061 --> 01:03:58,702
I promise I'll repay him as soon as possible. I swear.
- No.

1052
01:03:58,860 --> 01:03:59,860
[Sobbing]

1053
01:04:00,875 --> 01:04:03,038
[Tense music]

1054
01:04:04,562 --> 01:04:06,778
[Tense music]

1055
01:04:07,389 --> 01:04:08,618
Okay.

1056
01:04:12,437 --> 01:04:14,626
[Tense music]

1057
01:04:18,086 --> 01:04:19,917
[Tense music]

1058
01:04:23,797 --> 01:04:25,102
We'll figure it out.

1059
01:04:26,880 --> 01:04:29,131
[Sighs]

1060
01:04:36,264 --> 01:04:38,793
Are you ready?

1061
01:04:39,073 --> 01:04:41,999
[Jarring]

1062
01:04:42,422 --> 01:04:43,549
Take the card on top.

1063
01:04:45,502 --> 01:04:48,699
Look closely. Memorize it.
- Done.

1064
01:04:48,872 --> 01:04:51,639
Now fold it. Give that to me.

1065
01:04:51,764 --> 01:04:53,435
Hey, hold on to this.

1066
01:04:53,436 --> 01:04:54,770
Fold it. - Yes!

1067
01:04:54,972 --> 01:04:56,179
Give the card back.
- Oh, I have to give it back?

1068
01:04:56,180 --> 01:04:58,116
Obviously. I'm not looking at it.

1069
01:04:58,555 --> 01:04:59,780
Come here.

1070
01:05:00,165 --> 01:05:03,065
Are you eating something?
- Not at the moment, no.

1071
01:05:03,255 --> 01:05:04,554
Open your mouth?

1072
01:05:04,685 --> 01:05:06,060
Whoa!

1073
01:05:06,253 --> 01:05:07,830
[Laughing]

1074
01:05:08,097 --> 01:05:10,938
Now I am going to reveal to you what the card was.
- Yes.

1075
01:05:10,939 --> 01:05:13,759
[Indistinct chatter]

1076
01:05:14,214 --> 01:05:18,682
It was not a card with a digit.
- That's right.

1077
01:05:19,041 --> 01:05:20,592
And it was a red coloured card.

1078
01:05:21,143 --> 01:05:22,970
Oye-oye!

1079
01:05:22,971 --> 01:05:24,013
[Indistinct chatter]

1080
01:05:24,014 --> 01:05:26,688
It was a card of hearts.

1081
01:05:26,828 --> 01:05:28,589
Whoo!

1082
01:05:28,722 --> 01:05:33,055
And it was a king!
- Where's the proof?

1083
01:05:33,347 --> 01:05:35,867
It's right here.
Open your mouth, please.

1084
01:05:36,270 --> 01:05:36,989
[Chuckles]

1085
01:05:37,199 --> 01:05:37,738
Open?

1086
01:05:37,739 --> 01:05:39,266
Whoa!

1087
01:05:40,510 --> 01:05:41,850
[Cheering]

1088
01:05:41,981 --> 01:05:43,365
[Cheering]

1089
01:05:43,764 --> 01:05:47,890
The pizza is here.
- Guys, listen! I am not done with the tricks yet.

1090
01:05:47,891 --> 01:05:49,146
No, please! Siddhu, listen?

1091
01:05:49,479 --> 01:05:50,837
[Grunts]

1092
01:05:51,555 --> 01:05:52,555
[Coughs]

1093
01:05:54,148 --> 01:05:55,987
[Indistinct chatter]

1094
01:06:00,875 --> 01:06:01,917
[Sits]

1095
01:06:03,143 --> 01:06:04,143
[Knocking]

1096
01:06:05,368 --> 01:06:07,242
[Door opens]

1097
01:06:07,882 --> 01:06:10,133
[Singing]

1098
01:06:11,596 --> 01:06:12,883
You okay?

1099
01:06:15,388 --> 01:06:17,359
[Pulls]

1100
01:06:20,267 --> 01:06:21,835
[Kissing]

1101
01:06:22,816 --> 01:06:24,647
[Singing]

1102
01:06:27,581 --> 01:06:29,482
[Groaning]

1103
01:06:30,235 --> 01:06:32,276
[Laughs]

1104
01:06:34,510 --> 01:06:39,423
[Laughs]

1105
01:06:39,712 --> 01:06:41,035
[Sighs]

1106
01:06:41,639 --> 01:06:42,235
What's going on?

1107
01:06:42,524 --> 01:06:45,204
[Singing]

1108
01:06:46,518 --> 01:06:47,881
[Sighs]

1109
01:06:47,882 --> 01:06:49,812
[Cheering]

1110
01:06:50,451 --> 01:06:51,712
[Applauding]

1111
01:06:51,993 --> 01:06:54,253
[Applauding]

1112
01:06:54,430 --> 01:06:56,959
Mount Everest.
- Village.

1113
01:06:57,091 --> 01:06:58,096
[Grunts]

1114
01:06:58,097 --> 01:06:59,431
Bonfire?
- Tree?

1115
01:06:59,650 --> 01:07:01,563
Tribals.

1116
01:07:01,564 --> 01:07:02,844
Warli painting.

1117
01:07:02,845 --> 01:07:04,841
A triangle?
- Evolution!

1118
01:07:04,842 --> 01:07:08,855
Five, four, three, two, one!

1119
01:07:08,856 --> 01:07:14,188
Time up! Your time's up!
You lose! It's over. It's done.

1120
01:07:14,189 --> 01:07:15,353
What was the word?

1121
01:07:15,598 --> 01:07:16,764
It's Africa!

1122
01:07:16,903 --> 01:07:18,240
[Laughing]

1123
01:07:18,241 --> 01:07:19,755
[Indistinct chatter]

1124
01:07:19,756 --> 01:07:23,574
How is this Africa? You've
drawn everything except Africa.

1125
01:07:23,575 --> 01:07:26,170
These are the pyramids right here.
These are people dancing.

1126
01:07:26,319 --> 01:07:27,537
[Laughing]

1127
01:07:27,686 --> 01:07:29,096
[Clapping]

1128
01:07:29,097 --> 01:07:31,635
Sit down. You need a break.

1129
01:07:31,636 --> 01:07:34,482
You need to rest for ten minutes.

1130
01:07:34,483 --> 01:07:37,683
Why didn't you just draw the map of Africa.
It's basic. Everyone knows that much.

1131
01:07:37,855 --> 01:07:42,576
That's so basic. Isn't it so basic?
What does your T-shirt say?

1132
01:07:42,813 --> 01:07:43,813
[Chuckles]

1133
01:07:44,180 --> 01:07:45,922
Paraguay.
- Paraguay.

1134
01:07:46,246 --> 01:07:49,265
Paraguay. Betty, put on
the world map, will you?

1135
01:07:49,266 --> 01:07:51,344
[Indistinct chatter]

1136
01:07:51,642 --> 01:07:52,944
[Chuckles]

1137
01:07:52,945 --> 01:07:54,945
Enough now, you guys lost.
- Here is the world map.

1138
01:07:55,130 --> 01:07:56,976
Where is it then? Paraguay?

1139
01:07:58,380 --> 01:07:59,380
Look for it.

1140
01:07:59,569 --> 01:08:02,141
Why don't you show us?
- These two are playing their own game.

1141
01:08:02,142 --> 01:08:03,905
[Chuckles]

1142
01:08:04,518 --> 01:08:05,958
Come on, tell us.
Where is Paraguay?

1143
01:08:08,722 --> 01:08:10,842
Exactly where it was yesterday.

1144
01:08:11,376 --> 01:08:12,346
[Squealing]

1145
01:08:12,347 --> 01:08:15,230
No, no. This isn't time
for your comedy. Show us.

1146
01:08:15,514 --> 01:08:18,235
Let it be. Who gives a
shit about Paraguay?

1147
01:08:19,207 --> 01:08:22,413
Come on. It's so basic.
Why don't you Google it?

1148
01:08:22,693 --> 01:08:26,281
Do you want to? Paraguay?
Okay, okay. Okay.

1149
01:08:26,282 --> 01:08:29,166
Tell me, is it a country or a city?

1150
01:08:29,744 --> 01:08:30,857
[Soft whisper]

1151
01:08:31,934 --> 01:08:36,121
A country?
- Yes, 'a country' question mark? Or 'a country' full stop?

1152
01:08:36,401 --> 01:08:38,565
Come on!

1153
01:08:39,029 --> 01:08:41,743
Okay, guys enough. Enough, enough.

1154
01:08:41,744 --> 01:08:45,817
It's the capital of Argentina.
Got it? That's it. Done.

1155
01:08:46,757 --> 01:08:48,625
I had forgotten.
- It's okay!

1156
01:08:48,626 --> 01:08:51,660
It can happen.
- Of course, it can happen.

1157
01:08:52,465 --> 01:08:55,592
It's not! It's not the
capital of Argentina!

1158
01:08:55,759 --> 01:08:57,178
[Laughing]

1159
01:08:57,808 --> 01:08:59,233
Just say you don't know.
What's the problem?

1160
01:08:59,234 --> 01:09:00,994
If you don't know, you
don't know. So, what?

1161
01:09:01,391 --> 01:09:04,422
Okay, okay. Last question guys.

1162
01:09:05,972 --> 01:09:08,924
What language do
they speak in Paraguay?

1163
01:09:09,116 --> 01:09:10,116
Go for it.

1164
01:09:10,316 --> 01:09:13,146
Mexican? Italian?

1165
01:09:13,873 --> 01:09:17,136
Adriatic? Or Spanish?

1166
01:09:17,137 --> 01:09:18,906
Or none of the above.

1167
01:09:18,907 --> 01:09:20,544
[Chuckles]

1168
01:09:20,545 --> 01:09:24,130
Go for Phone-A-Friend.
Call your dad.

1169
01:09:24,305 --> 01:09:26,162
[Squealing]

1170
01:09:26,994 --> 01:09:27,929
Sorry.

1171
01:09:27,930 --> 01:09:32,030
Okay, okay, silence. So which
language do they speak in over there?

1172
01:09:32,407 --> 01:09:33,407
He's feeling shy.

1173
01:09:34,115 --> 01:09:35,115
[Whispering]

1174
01:09:38,381 --> 01:09:40,168
[Gulping]

1175
01:09:41,192 --> 01:09:43,811
What was the third option?
- What was it indeed?

1176
01:09:44,996 --> 01:09:46,763
I think it was 'Adriatic'.
- Adriatic.

1177
01:09:46,973 --> 01:09:48,033
[Chuckling]

1178
01:09:48,208 --> 01:09:49,391
[Laughing]

1179
01:09:50,451 --> 01:09:53,907
Adriatic is a sea.

1180
01:09:53,908 --> 01:09:55,540
[Laughing]

1181
01:09:55,741 --> 01:09:57,038
[Laughing]

1182
01:09:57,222 --> 01:09:58,693
[Laughing]

1183
01:09:58,824 --> 01:10:00,511
[Chuckling loudly]

1184
01:10:00,512 --> 01:10:03,274
[Laughter]

1185
01:10:04,246 --> 01:10:06,541
[Chuckles]

1186
01:10:07,006 --> 01:10:08,284
[Loud laughter]

1187
01:10:08,915 --> 01:10:10,246
[Laughs]

1188
01:10:10,430 --> 01:10:11,104
Bye.
- Bye.

1189
01:10:11,105 --> 01:10:12,410
Take care.
- Bye, Betty!

1190
01:10:13,251 --> 01:10:14,740
[Footsteps]

1191
01:10:15,914 --> 01:10:17,138
Hey, bye.
- Bye.

1192
01:10:17,139 --> 01:10:18,139
Take care.
- Yes.

1193
01:10:18,281 --> 01:10:20,865
See you.

1194
01:10:22,680 --> 01:10:25,481
Let's go, guys.
- Let's go.

1195
01:10:26,628 --> 01:10:27,628
The keys?

1196
01:10:28,415 --> 01:10:30,596
See you on the new year's eve. Bye.

1197
01:10:32,380 --> 01:10:35,433
Do you have them?
Let's go.

1198
01:10:39,547 --> 01:10:40,547
Come on.

1199
01:10:41,669 --> 01:10:43,719
[Footsteps]

1200
01:10:45,593 --> 01:10:46,303
What happened?

1201
01:10:46,496 --> 01:10:47,880
[Footsteps]

1202
01:10:48,214 --> 01:10:49,534
Was there news about the funding?

1203
01:10:50,104 --> 01:10:51,480
[Thunder rumbling]

1204
01:10:52,592 --> 01:10:56,341
Okay, come on. Get in the car.
We'll go home and talk. Let's go.

1205
01:10:57,042 --> 01:10:58,916
[Footsteps]

1206
01:11:01,535 --> 01:11:03,155
[Thuds]

1207
01:11:05,634 --> 01:11:07,955
[Sad music]

1208
01:11:09,138 --> 01:11:10,846
[Sad music]

1209
01:11:12,799 --> 01:11:14,972
[Sad music]

1210
01:11:15,464 --> 01:11:18,353
How can you treat me like this?

1211
01:11:18,887 --> 01:11:20,805
[Tense music]

1212
01:11:22,390 --> 01:11:24,913
[Thunder rumbling]

1213
01:11:25,859 --> 01:11:27,129
Such hatred?

1214
01:11:27,593 --> 01:11:29,258
[Tense music]

1215
01:11:32,839 --> 01:11:33,839
This much?

1216
01:11:34,287 --> 01:11:36,179
[Tense music]

1217
01:11:39,542 --> 01:11:41,855
[Tense music]

1218
01:11:42,853 --> 01:11:44,605
[Clangs]

1219
01:11:45,104 --> 01:11:47,049
So, the entire car is made here?

1220
01:11:47,180 --> 01:11:48,801
Most of its interior parts are.

1221
01:11:49,239 --> 01:11:51,580
Different auto components
are made here in the press shop.

1222
01:11:51,726 --> 01:11:54,371
We weld them together and
send them to the company.

1223
01:11:54,862 --> 01:11:57,103
The final assembly happens
in the respective companies.

1224
01:11:57,104 --> 01:11:58,471
[Clangs]

1225
01:11:58,630 --> 01:12:01,007
It's Sunday today.
- So?

1226
01:12:01,008 --> 01:12:03,236
I thought you called
because it was a holiday.

1227
01:12:04,614 --> 01:12:07,305
Can't I wish to meet
you on a working day?

1228
01:12:07,306 --> 01:12:09,069
[Clangs]

1229
01:12:09,463 --> 01:12:11,241
How is work?
- Great.

1230
01:12:11,822 --> 01:12:15,104
Good. So where are you opening the first studio?
- Good morning, Sir!

1231
01:12:16,234 --> 01:12:18,406
Thank you for not calling it a gym.

1232
01:12:20,339 --> 01:12:23,539
Where do I come for the opening then? When is it?
- Calm down. I'm not there yet.

1233
01:12:24,922 --> 01:12:28,002
You must have ordered the equipment by
now, right? Have you secured the space?

1234
01:12:28,304 --> 01:12:31,606
I have a couple of options in mind. But I
haven't confirmed anything in person yet.

1235
01:12:32,580 --> 01:12:35,140
As long as the money is sorted,
everything else falls into place.

1236
01:12:35,547 --> 01:12:37,957
It is as good as done.

1237
01:12:39,172 --> 01:12:40,812
Where is the finance
coming from finally?

1238
01:12:41,250 --> 01:12:43,834
There are a couple of
people. It's all happening.

1239
01:12:45,385 --> 01:12:49,650
Let's see. It'll happen.
Consider it done!

1240
01:12:53,347 --> 01:12:56,202
What if it doesn't work?
- What?

1241
01:12:57,847 --> 01:12:59,276
What if the plan doesn't work out?

1242
01:13:01,047 --> 01:13:02,395
I don't have the option to fail.

1243
01:13:04,422 --> 01:13:06,415
Why not?
- I just don't.

1244
01:13:07,755 --> 01:13:09,306
Everyone has the option to fail.

1245
01:13:10,462 --> 01:13:13,719
If you realize that things are not working
out despite trying your level best,

1246
01:13:13,720 --> 01:13:15,481
it's okay to give up, you know.

1247
01:13:16,464 --> 01:13:17,925
That's not a possibility for me.

1248
01:13:19,014 --> 01:13:21,366
Have you called me here
to convince me to give up?

1249
01:13:21,367 --> 01:13:22,818
What's wrong with giving up?

1250
01:13:23,303 --> 01:13:27,577
Why must every single person have a success story of some kind?
- They must.

1251
01:13:28,722 --> 01:13:30,126
Why?
- Because they must.

1252
01:13:30,398 --> 01:13:32,211
[Clangs]

1253
01:13:33,214 --> 01:13:34,707
But why?

1254
01:13:36,214 --> 01:13:37,782
I don't have an explanation.

1255
01:13:38,714 --> 01:13:41,921
No, that's not okay. If you think everyone must have
a success story, you have to be able to say why.

1256
01:13:41,922 --> 01:13:45,174
Anything can be made to seem sensible
if you say it at gunpoint like this.

1257
01:13:45,349 --> 01:13:46,646
[Machinery sound]

1258
01:13:47,047 --> 01:13:48,927
So, what I am saying
does seem sensible to you?

1259
01:13:49,063 --> 01:13:50,947
[Tense music]

1260
01:13:52,585 --> 01:13:53,585
Leave me alone.

1261
01:13:54,678 --> 01:13:56,439
[Machine clanging]

1262
01:13:58,155 --> 01:13:59,618
[Machine clanging]

1263
01:14:02,211 --> 01:14:03,971
[Clanging]

1264
01:14:05,636 --> 01:14:07,063
[Machine clanging]

1265
01:14:07,571 --> 01:14:09,679
[Machine clanging]

1266
01:14:09,680 --> 01:14:12,639
What is the problem?
Your father is a diamond merchant.

1267
01:14:13,830 --> 01:14:17,789
At least four more generations in your
family need not work at all. Why bother then?

1268
01:14:17,938 --> 01:14:18,846
[Machine clanging]

1269
01:14:18,847 --> 01:14:20,527
Do you only work to
be able to make money?

1270
01:14:21,442 --> 01:14:23,167
[Machine clangs]

1271
01:14:24,422 --> 01:14:28,948
Absolutely not. But I know why I
work. I'm asking you why you do.

1272
01:14:29,097 --> 01:14:30,840
[Machine clanging]

1273
01:14:32,277 --> 01:14:34,037
[Machine whirring]

1274
01:14:35,036 --> 01:14:36,179
[Machine whirring]

1275
01:14:36,180 --> 01:14:37,532
I want to prove a point.

1276
01:14:39,582 --> 01:14:40,582
To whom?

1277
01:14:44,805 --> 01:14:45,805
No one.

1278
01:14:53,027 --> 01:14:54,595
[Clanging]

1279
01:14:56,303 --> 01:14:57,745
[Footsteps]

1280
01:14:57,746 --> 01:14:59,623
[Clanging]

1281
01:15:02,102 --> 01:15:04,099
[Whirring]

1282
01:15:05,623 --> 01:15:07,077
[Indistinct chatter]

1283
01:15:08,391 --> 01:15:09,391
[Clang]

1284
01:15:16,526 --> 01:15:17,526
Thank you very much.

1285
01:15:19,469 --> 01:15:21,939
[Clang]

1286
01:15:25,294 --> 01:15:26,294
[Clang]

1287
01:15:27,028 --> 01:15:28,028
How's work?

1288
01:15:28,806 --> 01:15:30,112
[Ruffling]

1289
01:15:31,951 --> 01:15:36,655
Could you please take the Octopus?
I won't be able to eat it.

1290
01:15:36,882 --> 01:15:37,882
[Soft music]

1291
01:15:37,968 --> 01:15:38,968
Give it to me.

1292
01:15:39,493 --> 01:15:40,587
[Clang]

1293
01:15:44,091 --> 01:15:46,833
Work?
- All good.

1294
01:15:48,841 --> 01:15:50,300
It was tough initially but

1295
01:15:50,301 --> 01:15:53,421
this year our company has released two
new games into the international market.

1296
01:15:53,647 --> 01:15:54,647
Hmm.

1297
01:15:54,955 --> 01:15:56,355
How come you turned to video games?

1298
01:15:57,571 --> 01:16:00,663
Once I stopped trying to prove a
point to anybody else, it found me.

1299
01:16:02,686 --> 01:16:03,686
[Munching]

1300
01:16:05,305 --> 01:16:06,985
And how was the
meeting you came here for?

1301
01:16:07,805 --> 01:16:08,805
Not bad.

1302
01:16:10,369 --> 01:16:14,451
They've agreed to let us use
the new software they've developed.

1303
01:16:15,117 --> 01:16:16,326
Congratulations.

1304
01:16:18,170 --> 01:16:19,170
[Chopping]

1305
01:16:20,237 --> 01:16:21,757
Could you please
also take the Shrimp?

1306
01:16:24,222 --> 01:16:25,222
Sure.

1307
01:16:25,318 --> 01:16:26,973
[Soft music]

1308
01:16:27,735 --> 01:16:28,874
[Clang]

1309
01:16:29,373 --> 01:16:30,792
[Clincking]

1310
01:16:31,563 --> 01:16:33,061
[Clutter]

1311
01:16:35,067 --> 01:16:36,067
[Thud]

1312
01:16:36,170 --> 01:16:38,050
I don't want to come in
between the two of you.

1313
01:16:38,150 --> 01:16:39,910
[Soft music]

1314
01:16:40,580 --> 01:16:41,580
What should I do?

1315
01:16:42,669 --> 01:16:43,669
[Clang]

1316
01:16:44,658 --> 01:16:46,007
It hasn't been easy for her.

1317
01:16:46,585 --> 01:16:47,536
[Sighs]

1318
01:16:47,537 --> 01:16:49,913
She has taken a lot of
time and effort to build her world.

1319
01:16:51,858 --> 01:16:55,896
Now, Haru-san, Nori-san, Kartu and
I together make her whole.

1320
01:16:56,316 --> 01:16:57,316
[Inhales]

1321
01:16:57,490 --> 01:16:59,530
So, you're not going to
be able to pick and choose.

1322
01:17:00,459 --> 01:17:02,684
'I'll take the Tuna
but not the Octopus.'

1323
01:17:02,973 --> 01:17:03,674
[Tense music]

1324
01:17:03,875 --> 01:17:05,475
'The Salmon is okay
but not the Shrimp.'

1325
01:17:05,697 --> 01:17:07,186
[Tense music]

1326
01:17:07,335 --> 01:17:10,305
Not possible. Okay?

1327
01:17:11,487 --> 01:17:13,283
[Suspenseful music]

1328
01:17:14,579 --> 01:17:16,716
[Suspenseful music]

1329
01:17:17,540 --> 01:17:19,458
[Clanging]

1330
01:17:21,280 --> 01:17:22,280
[Thuds]

1331
01:17:35,995 --> 01:17:40,742
I'm taking all the papers.
You know our bank manager?

1332
01:17:41,671 --> 01:17:42,967
Banerjee?
- Banerjee, yes.

1333
01:17:44,334 --> 01:17:46,134
He said that the
meeting is just a formality.

1334
01:17:48,330 --> 01:17:49,490
The loan should come through.

1335
01:17:55,256 --> 01:17:56,299
Consider it done.

1336
01:17:58,585 --> 01:17:59,662
[Sighs]

1337
01:18:01,826 --> 01:18:02,851
[Rubbing hands]

1338
01:18:06,652 --> 01:18:07,896
[Footsteps]

1339
01:18:08,617 --> 01:18:12,048
Let's buy a new laptop tomorrow.
A brand new one.

1340
01:18:12,179 --> 01:18:13,869
Hmm.

1341
01:18:14,080 --> 01:18:15,080
Umm.

1342
01:18:15,972 --> 01:18:17,434
[Clock ticks]

1343
01:18:18,039 --> 01:18:21,140
Hey? Hey!

1344
01:18:21,402 --> 01:18:22,532
[Clock ticks]

1345
01:18:24,599 --> 01:18:25,992
[Clock ticks]

1346
01:18:26,518 --> 01:18:27,518
Shall we celebrate today?

1347
01:18:28,805 --> 01:18:30,319
Fuji-san. Noon.

1348
01:18:32,815 --> 01:18:34,567
[Smooches]

1349
01:18:35,364 --> 01:18:36,364
[Smooching]

1350
01:18:38,010 --> 01:18:39,010
